5000|$|It {{describes}} the tenuous peace that {{existed between the}} two countries as a result of both governments being terrified at the prospect of a world-destroying nuclear war. The term is usually used for rhetorical purposes, and was probably coined by Lester Pearson in June 1955 at the 10th anniversary of the signing of the UN Charter: [...] "the <b>balance</b> <b>of</b> <b>terror</b> has replaced the balance of power".|$|E
5000|$|Ring <b>of</b> <b>Terror</b> {{received}} generally negative reviews. A {{review in}} Fight Night on Channel 9: Saturday Night Horror Films on New York's WOR-TV, 1973-1987 by James Arena gave Ring <b>of</b> <b>Terror</b> a C, but noted that [...] "it was just off-beat {{enough to hold}} my interest." [...] Ring <b>of</b> <b>Terror</b> was included in Steve Miller's 150 Movies You Should Die Before You See. Miller gave Ring <b>of</b> <b>Terror</b> five thumbs down. He especially criticized {{the fact that the}} actors cast as college students were far too old, noting that they were in their late 30's and early 40's. Michael Adams, in his book Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies: A Film Critic's Year-Long Quest to Find the Worst Movie Ever Made, reviewed Ring <b>of</b> <b>Terror</b> and found it to be dull and full of padding. Like Miller, he noted that the actors were far too old to play college students. He pointed out that lead George E. Mather was 42 when he filmed Ring <b>of</b> <b>Terror.</b> VideoHound's Golden Movie Retriever called Ring <b>of</b> <b>Terror</b> a [...] "cheaply made flop." ...|$|R
